Welcome to notebook two of the Java track. Notebook one gave us the alphabet of Java. Types, variables, expressions, statements, and control flow. This notebook gives us the sentences. We will look at object oriented Java, which is where you start modelling a domain rather than just computing values. By the end of this session you will be comfortable with classes, fields, constructors, methods, encapsulation, inheritance, abstract classes, and interfaces. And you will know the modern additions that change how Java code looks today. Records, sealed types, and pattern matching for switch. These three together are the single biggest shift in style between old Java and modern Java, and they are the shapes that Spring will lean on later, so it is worth getting fluent with them now.

Let us start with the most fundamental shape. The class. In Java, almost everything lives inside a class. A class is a blueprint. It declares what data an object holds, which we call fields, and what an object can do, which we call methods. You then create objects, also called instances, from the class using the keyword new.

Think of it this way. The class Point describes the shape of a two dimensional point. It says every point has an integer x coordinate and an integer y coordinate, and that every point knows how to compute its distance from the origin. The class itself is not a point. It is the recipe for points. When you write new Point of three comma four, you get an actual instance of Point, one whose x is three and whose y is four. You can create as many instances as you like. They share the recipe but they each carry their own data.

A class definition has three main ingredients. Fields, declared inside the class body but outside any method, are the data each instance holds. The constructor is a special block that runs once when you create an object with the keyword new. It has the same name as the class and no return type. It is where you assign the incoming arguments to the fields. And methods are the behaviour the instance can perform. They live alongside the fields and can read or modify them.

One small but important keyword. The keyword this. Inside a method or constructor, this is the implicit reference to the current instance. You use this dot x to mean the field x of this instance. You use it most often when a constructor parameter name shadows a field name. If your constructor takes a parameter called x, and your field is also called x, then this dot x equals x means assign the parameter to the field.

Now let us talk about visibility. Java has four access levels that control who can see each field and method. The keyword public means visible from anywhere. The keyword protected means visible from the same package and from any subclass. No modifier at all means visible only from the same package, which we call package private. And the keyword private means visible only from inside the same class.

The standard practice in Java is private fields and public methods. The class owns its data. The outside world interacts through methods. This pattern is the original meaning of the word encapsulation. The class hides its internal representation behind a small public surface. Hiding data behind methods is what lets you change the internal representation later, say switching from a long number of cents to a big decimal, without breaking every caller in your codebase. Without this discipline, every change to the inside of a class ripples out into the entire system.

A class can have multiple constructors. Same name, different parameter lists. One constructor can delegate to another with the call this open paren, arguments, close paren. This is how you provide convenient defaults without duplicating logic. For example, a Rectangle class might have one constructor that takes width and height, and a second convenience constructor that takes just one number, side, and delegates to the primary constructor with side and side as both arguments. That gives you a square shortcut without having to write the assignment logic twice.

Method overloading works the same way. Multiple methods can share the same name as long as their parameter lists differ. The compiler picks the right method at the call site based on the argument types. Overloading is purely a compile time mechanism. It is not the same as overriding, which we are about to meet.

Now we come to inheritance. A class can extend another class. You write the keyword extends, then the name of the parent class. The class you extend is called the superclass. Your class is called the subclass. A subclass inherits every non private field and method of its superclass. It can add new ones, and it can override existing ones to change their behaviour.

In our example, the class Animal has a name field and a method called speak. The class Dog extends Animal. The Dog class inherits the name field for free. The Dog constructor calls super, the keyword that means call the superclass constructor, passing the name through. And the Dog class overrides the speak method so that when you call speak on a Dog instance, you get back the string rex barks instead of the generic version.

Three things to internalise here. First, the keyword extends establishes the parent child relationship. A class in Java can extend exactly one other class. There is no multiple inheritance of classes. Second, the call super open paren, arguments, close paren, calls the superclass constructor. It must be the first statement in the subclass constructor if you use it. Third, the annotation at sign Override. This is a built in annotation that you put on a method to declare that this method is meant to override one in the superclass. If the signature does not actually match, for example because you misspelled the method name, the compiler errors out instead of silently creating a new method that is unrelated to the parent. You should always use at sign Override on overriding methods. It catches a class of bugs that are otherwise very easy to miss.

Inheritance gives us polymorphism, which is one of the most important ideas in object oriented programming. Because Dog is a kind of Animal, a variable of type Animal can hold a Dog. When you call the speak method on that variable, the java virtual machine dispatches to the actual runtime type's version of the method. So if you have a list of Animal, and some of them are Dog instances, the loop that calls speak on each one will see Dog dot speak run for the Dog instances, even though your loop was written against the Animal type. This is exactly how frameworks like Spring let you swap implementations without changing the calling code. You program against an interface or a base class. Spring injects the actual implementation at runtime. Polymorphism is what makes this seamless.

Sometimes a base class can describe part of the shape but cannot meaningfully implement every method. Only its subclasses can fill in the gaps. In that case, you declare the class with the keyword abstract, and you also declare the unfinished methods as abstract. An abstract method has no body. Just a signature followed by a semicolon. You cannot instantiate an abstract class directly. The compiler will reject new of an abstract class.

A typical example is a Shape class with an abstract method area. The shape itself cannot compute its area in general. Only specific shapes can. So Circle extends Shape and implements area as pi times radius squared. Square extends Shape and implements area as side times side. The Shape class can still have concrete methods, like a describe method that calls area and embeds it in a string. Those concrete methods are shared by all subclasses. Abstract classes are the right tool when you have shared state, or shared partial implementation, across a family of types. When you only have shared behaviour contracts, with no state to share, interfaces are usually a better fit.

That brings us to interfaces. An interface is a pure contract. A set of method signatures with no fields and no state. Any class can implement any number of interfaces, and the compiler enforces that the implementing class provides every method the interface declares.

The keyword to implement an interface is implements. You can write a single class that implements many interfaces. So while a class can extend only one other class, it can implement many interfaces. This is how Java gives you a controlled form of multiple inheritance. You inherit behaviour contracts from many interfaces, but you inherit state and implementation from at most one superclass.

Two key contrasts between interfaces and abstract classes. First, a class can implement many interfaces but extend only one class. Second, an interface holds no instance state. No instance fields, other than constants. No constructor. It is a behavioural contract, not a partial implementation.

Since Java eight, interfaces can carry concrete methods too. A default method is a method on the interface that has a body. Every implementing class inherits this default method for free, but the implementer is allowed to override it if they want. The keyword default goes before the return type. A static method on an interface is a utility method that belongs to the interface itself. You call it as Greeter dot friendly, not on an instance.

Default methods are how the java util Collection and Stream application programming interfaces were extended in Java eight without breaking every existing implementation. They are also why an interface with a single abstract method, sometimes called a functional interface, can be implemented by a lambda. You will see plenty of that pattern in notebook four.

When a type has a small closed set of values, an enum is the right shape. Days of the week. http methods like get, post, put, delete. Payment statuses like pending, paid, refunded. You declare an enum with the keyword enum and list the constants inside braces. Each constant is a singleton instance of the enum type. There is exactly one HttpMethod dot POST in the entire program, no matter how many times you reference it.

Enums work beautifully with switch. You can write a switch expression on an enum value, with one arm per constant, and the compiler will warn you if you miss a case. The Java enum type also gives you two helper methods for free. The static values method returns an array of all the constants, in declaration order. The static value of method takes a string and returns the matching constant, or throws if no match is found.

Java enums are more powerful than the integer flag enums you might know from C or older languages. Java enums can carry fields, can have a constructor, and can have methods. So an HttpStatus enum can store both the numeric code and a description for each constant. You list the constructor arguments next to each constant declaration. OK opens with two hundred and the string ok. NOT FOUND opens with four hundred four and the string not found. Behind the scenes, each enum constant is a full instance of the enum class, complete with its own field values.

Now we come to the first of the three modern features that change how Java code looks today. Records. A huge fraction of classes in real codebases are data carriers. A fixed set of fields. A constructor that assigns them. Accessors that read them. Plus the equals method, the hashCode method, and the toString method. That is dozens of lines of boilerplate for a class that holds three values. In old Java you wrote all of that by hand, or used a code generation library like Lombok to hide it.

Java sixteen introduced records. The keyword is record. You write public record User open paren, the components in order, close paren, open brace, close brace. That is the whole class. The compiler generates everything for you. A canonical constructor that takes the components in declaration order. One accessor per component, named the same as the component. Note that the accessor is just email, not get email. Modern Java drops the get prefix for record components. The equals method, derived from all components. The hashCode method, derived from all components. The toString method, which lists every component with its value.

All record fields are final, which means once an instance is created, you cannot reassign the components. Records are immutable by construction. This makes them safe to share across threads, safe to use as map keys, and easy to reason about.

Records are not just dumb data bags. You can add methods. You can override the accessors. You can implement interfaces. And you can validate the components in a compact constructor. The compact constructor is a special syntax. You write public Money open brace, then your validation code, then close brace. The implicit field assignment runs after your block. So you can check that the amount in cents is not negative, or that the currency string is exactly three letters, and throw an illegal argument exception if not. Records are not just for data classes. They are for any small, immutable, value oriented type that pairs a few components together.

The second modern feature is sealed types. Normally a class or an interface in Java is open to extension by anyone, anywhere, at any time. Anyone in any package or any project can declare a new subclass. Sealed types let you say, these are the only types allowed to extend me. The compiler enforces the restriction. You write public sealed interface Shape permits Circle comma Square comma Triangle. Now no class anywhere in the world is allowed to implement Shape except those three. Java records pair beautifully with sealed types, because each subtype is just a one line record.

The third modern feature is pattern matching for switch. Modern Java's switch can do more than match constants. It can match types, and it can destructure records, all in one place. The syntax is case followed by a type pattern, followed by the arrow, followed by the expression to return. If the type pattern includes the record components, like case Circle open paren double r close paren arrow, then the components are pulled out of the record into local names you can use in the right hand side.

When you combine sealed types with pattern matching, you get exhaustiveness checking. The compiler knows the complete set of subtypes of a sealed type. It can verify that your switch covers every one of them. If you add a fourth shape later, every switch on Shape becomes a compile error until you update it. This is enormously valuable for refactoring. You change the type, and the compiler tells you exactly which call sites need to be updated.

The combination of sealed types, records, and pattern matching is Java's answer to what other languages call algebraic data types. Scala has them. Rust has them. Kotlin has them. Now Java has them too. They let you model a closed family of variants with very little code, and they let the compiler help you handle every variant correctly.

Pattern matching also supports guards. A guard is a boolean condition that must hold for the case to match. You write the keyword when followed by the condition. So you can write case Circle c when c dot radius is greater than one hundred arrow huge circle, and a separate case Circle c arrow circle. The first case matches only huge circles. The second catches everything else.

Finally, a few words on annotations. An annotation is metadata you attach to a class, method, field, or parameter. The compiler and various libraries read annotations to change behaviour or generate code. You will use annotations constantly once we reach Spring, where every important Spring concept, like component, autowired, rest controller, and request mapping, is encoded as an annotation.

Three annotations ship with the java development kit itself, and you should learn them now. The annotation at sign Override declares that the annotated method overrides a superclass or interface method. The compiler verifies the claim. If the signature drifts, you get a compile error. Always use it. The annotation at sign Deprecated marks a class, method, or field as obsolete. Callers see a compiler warning. You can also pass arguments to deprecated, like since equals two point zero and for removal equals true, to give callers more information. And the annotation at sign Suppress Warnings tells the compiler to silence a specific warning category for the annotated element. Use it sparingly, only when you have a real reason to override the compiler's warning.

That wraps notebook two. You can now model a domain in Java using classes, inheritance, interfaces, and the modern triplet of records, sealed types, and pattern matching. You also know how to read built in annotations, which is the doorway to Spring's entire programming model.

Notebook three turns to collections and generics. The list type. The set type. The map type. The immutable factories like List dot of and Map dot of. Generic type parameters with angle bracket T. And the variance rules question mark extends T and question mark super T, which show up everywhere in real Java application programming interfaces.
